{"PageNumber":8,"Angle":0,"RotatedAngle":0,"Height":817,"Width":1089,"OriginHeight":0,"OriginWidth":0,"Elements":[{"Index":0,"Type":"title","Text":"#  Types of System Requirements","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":27,"Y":63},"LeftTop":{"X":27,"Y":26},"RightBottom":{"X":521,"Y":63},"RightTop":{"X":521,"Y":26}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":1,"Type":"title","Text":"##  Domain Requirements","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":96,"Y":206},"LeftTop":{"X":96,"Y":177},"RightBottom":{"X":394,"Y":206},"RightTop":{"X":394,"Y":177}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":2,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"• Domain requirements are a type of software requirement that describe specific features or capabilities that are unique to a particular application domain. A domain is a specific area of expertise or knowledge, such as healthcare, finance, or manufacturing, and domain requirements are those requirements that are specific to that domain.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":119,"Y":466},"LeftTop":{"X":119,"Y":232},"RightBottom":{"X":972,"Y":466},"RightTop":{"X":972,"Y":232}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":3,"Type":"paragraph","Text":"• For example, a healthcare domain requirement might specify that the software needs to be able to store and manage patient records, or that it must adhere to certain regulatory requirements related to patient confidentiality.","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":119,"Y":643},"LeftTop":{"X":119,"Y":488},"RightBottom":{"X":998,"Y":643},"RightTop":{"X":998,"Y":488}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImagePath":"","group_id":-1,"group_type":""},{"Index":4,"Type":"footer","Text":"7","Level":0,"Polygon":{"LeftBottom":{"X":1054,"Y":785},"LeftTop":{"X":1054,"Y":768},"RightBottom":{"X":1064,"Y":785},"RightTop":{"X":1064,"Y":768}},"InsetImageName":"","Elements":null,"ImageP